# Data description

Data supporting: Fitzpatrick LJ, Cayuela H, Olsson M, While GM, Wapstra E.
Actuarial senescence and reproduction diverge across contrasting thermal 
environments in a wild ectotherm. Ecology Letters (submitted 2026).

Species: Carinascincus ocellatus (spotted snow skink)
Populations: Warm lowland (OR = Orford) and 
             Cool highland (CP = Central Plateau), Tasmania, Australia
Study period: 2000–2024

---

## Data files

### BOM.csv
Daily climate records from Bureau of Meteorology weather stations 
Liawenee (96033, highland) and Orford (92027, lowland), 2001–2023.
Columns: Site (OR = warm lowland, CP = cool highland), Year, Month, Day, 
         Maxtemp (°C), Mintemp (°C), Rainfall (mm)

### census_data.csv
Individual female capture-recapture records, 2000–2024.
Used as input for Bayesian Survival Trajectory Analysis (BaSTA).
Columns: Year, FemID (female identifier), Site (OR = warm lowland, CP = cool highland),
         Age (years), DeathYear (confirmed death; 
         NA = individual not observed to die, i.e. right-censored)

### growth_data.csv
Body size measurements for C. ocellatus across all life stages.
Columns: FCODE (female toe code), FEMID (female identifier), 
         Site (OR = warm lowland, CP = cool highland),
         Age (years), FSVLAFTER (snout-vent length, mm)
Note: Age 0.01 = measurement at birth; Age 0.75 = post-winter juvenile measurement.
      FEMID and FCODE are blank for juveniles as individual IDs are assigned at maturity.

### reproductive_data.csv
Annual reproductive records for individually identified adult females.
Columns: Year, FemID (female identifier), Site (OR = warm lowland, CP = cool highland),
         Age (years), Clutch (litter size = number of offspring at parturition)
Note: Records with Clutch = 0 or NA are excluded from the processed dataset.
      Zero litter sizes could not be distinguished from missing data as non-gravid 
      status was not consistently recorded throughout the study period. Analyses 
      therefore model conditional fertility (litter size given reproduction occurred).

